Two cottage mills, named Holebottom and Millcroft, are also known to have existed.<ref name="Oldham Borough Guide"/> Little is known about them except that Holebottom was built in the mid-17th century and was not demolished until around 300 years later.

==Governance==
===Civic history===
[[Image:ShawandCromptonEmblem1.png|thumb|right|This emblem, introduced in 1987, is found at the parish border markers of Shaw and Crompton, as well as on some street furniture.]]
Crompton was recorded in 1212 as being part of the [[thegn]]age estate of Kaskenmoor, which was held on behalf of [[John of England|King John]] by [[Roger de Montbegon]] and [[William de Nevill]].<ref name= "County of Lanc"/> The Shaw and Crompton area later formed a [[township (England)|township]] within the ancient ecclesiastical parish of [[Prestwich-cum-Oldham]], in the [[Salford (hundred)|hundred of Salford]].<ref name= "County of Lanc"/> From 1894 to 1974, Shaw and Crompton formed its own local government district, [[Crompton Urban District]], and lay within the [[Administrative counties of England|administrative county]] of Lancashire.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/unit_page.jsp?u_id=10137007 |title=A vision of Crompton UD |author=A Vision of Britain through Time |accessdate=2007-06-15}}</ref>

Under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], the town's independent [[Urban District]] status was abolished, and Shaw and Crompton has, since [[1 April]] [[1974]], formed part of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]], within [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name="GM Gazetteer"/><ref>HMSO. Local Government Act 1972. 1972 c.70.</ref> Since 1987, Shaw and Crompton has had [[civil parish]] status, and its own [[parish council]], giving it some limited local government autonomy from that of the wider Metropolitan Borough of Oldham, and including the status as a statutory consultee on local [[planning permission|planning applications]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/council/councillors.htm|title=Know Your Councillors|author=Oldham Metropolitan Borough Council|publisher=oldham.gov.uk|accessdate=2007-07-07}}</ref> The parish council comprises 14 locally elected members, including three who also act as councillors to the wider Oldham [[local authority]]. The parish council is consulted in planning applications that affect the area.<ref name="Shaw and Royton Area">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/shaw___royton_area_plan_-_april_04b.pdf |format=PDF| title=Shaw and Royton Area Plan |author=Oldham Metropolitan Borough Council |date= January 2004 |accessdate=2007-06-21}}</ref> Shaw and Crompton does not have a [[mayor]], but does have a [[town crier]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1006/1006208_peter_cries_foul_over_picture_on_bnp_leaflet.html|title=Peter cries foul over picture on BNP leaflet|author=Ciara Leeming|date=[[2007]]-[[05-04]]|accessdate=2007-07-09}}</ref> a purely ceremonial role.

===Parliamentary representation===
Shaw and Crompton forms part of the parliamentary constituency of [[Oldham East and Saddleworth (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham East and Saddleworth]], and is represented in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] by [[Phil Woolas]], a member of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.communities.gov.uk/index.asp?id=1122759 |title=Phil Woolas MP|publisher=Communities.gov.uk |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> From 1832 until 1950, the town lay within the parliamentary constituency of [[Oldham (UK Parliament constituency)|Oldham]],<ref name="1911 Encyclo">{{cite web |url=http://www.1911encyclopedia.org/Crompton |title=Crompton |publisher=1911encyclopedia.org |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> which was represented in the House of Commons by [[Winston Churchill]] between 1900 and 1906.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.winstonchurchill.org/i4a/pages/index.cfm?pageid=710|title=Churchill and...Politics; All the Elections Churchill Ever Contested|author=The Churchill Centre|publisher=winstonchurchill.org|date=|accessdate=2007-07-07}}</ref> Churchill once stayed at [[Crompton Hall]], and letters written by him describe how peaceful and tranquil he thought the area to be.<ref>{{Citation | last =Greer, S.|title=More housing will make lives a misery|newspaper=[[Oldham Advertiser]]|pages=24|year=2006|date=[[2006-06-15]]}}</ref>

==Geography==
{{further|[[Geography of Greater Manchester]]}}
[[Image:OldhamBoroughsShawCrompton.png|thumb|left|The [[Metropolitan Borough of Oldham]], highlighting Shaw and Crompton in red.]]
At {{coor dms|53|34|39|N|2|5|32|W|city}} (53.5777, -2.0928) Shaw and Crompton lies along the eastern edge of the ancient Lancashire border; [[West Yorkshire]] and the [[Pennines|Pennine hills]] are close to the east. The larger towns of [[Rochdale]] and Oldham lie to the northwest and south respectively; [[Royton]] is {{convert|1.2|mi|km|1}} west-southwest. There are no [[List of motorways in the United Kingdom|motorway]]s in Shaw and Crompton, though a heavy rail line bisects the town from north to south.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmpte.com/content.cfm?subcategory_id=3367920|title=Park & Ride - Shaw and Crompton rail station|author=[[GMPTE]]|publisher=gmpte.com|date=|accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref> The town has a [[post office]] under the [[OL postcode area|Oldham post town]]. The territory of the civil parish is given as {{convert|4.5|sqmi|sqkm|1}}. For purposes of the [[Office for National Statistics]], Shaw and Crompton forms part of the [[Greater Manchester Urban Area]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/downloads/census2001/ks_urban_north_part_5.pdf|format=PDF| title=Census 2001:Key Statistics for urban areas in the North; Map 3|author=[[Office for National Statistics]]|publisher=statistics.gov.uk|accessdate=2007-07-09|date=2001}}</ref> with [[Manchester City Centre]] itself {{convert|8.7|mi|km|1}} southwest of Shaw and Crompton.

Described in [[Samuel Lewis (publisher)|Samuel Lewis]]'s ''A Topographical Dictionary of England'' (1848) as located in "a bleak situation",<ref name="Top of England">{{cite book|last=Lewis|first=Samuel|title=A Topographical Dictionary of England; 'Crofton - Cropthorne'|publisher=Institute of Historical Research|date=1848|pages=729<U+2013>33|isbn=978-0806315089}}</ref> Shaw and Crompton is in the valley of the [[River Beal]], which runs northward through the town towards the village of [[Newhey]]. The land to the east of the town steadily rises, reaching a height of {{convert|1283|ft|m|0}} at the summit of [[Crompton Moor]]. To the west, the land reaches around {{convert|699|ft|m|0}} at [[High Crompton]], and from these two highpoints the surface slopes away in all directions. The [[River Irk]] rises on Shaw and Crompton's western boundary with [[Royton]].<ref name="County of Lanc">{{cite book |last=Brownbill|first=J|coauthors=William Farrer|title=A History of the County of Lancaster: Volume 5|publisher=Victoria County History|date=1911|pages=108<U+2013>12|isbn=978-0712910552}}</ref> The soils of the town are broadly sterile.<ref name="Top of England"/>

Shaw and Crompton's [[built environment]] is somewhat unremarkable, broadly following the [[urban structure]] of most [[List of towns in England|towns in England]], consisting of residential dwellings centred around a [[High Street]] in the [[town centre]], which is the local centre of commerce.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/shaw_and_crompton_tc_masterplan_oct06.pdf|format=PDF| title=Shaw and Crompton Town Centre Masterplan|author=[[Ordnance Survey]]|publisher=Oldham Metropolitan Borough Council|date=2006|accessdate=2007-07-03}}</ref> There is a mixture of low-density [[urban areas]], [[suburb]]s, semi-rural and [[rural]] locations in Shaw and Crompton, but overwhelmingly the [[land use]] in the town is residential. Generally, property in the centre, west, and south of the town is older and smaller in contrast to that found in the east and north. 

