===Divisions and suburbs===
Shaw was originally a sub-district of Crompton,<ref>{{cite book |last= Hanyes |first=H |date=2004 |title=Rochdale Photographic Memories |publisher= Francis Frith Collection |isbn= 1-85937-846-3}}</ref> and appears to have its origins as the centre of Crompton because of the siting of a small chapel there dating back to around the 16th century.<ref name="Look Crompton">{{cite book |last=Hunt |first=Julian | coauthors = Frances Stott |date=1988 |title=Looking Back at Crompton |publisher=Oldham Education & Leisure |isbn= 0-902809-17-2}}</ref> In 1835, Shaw was noted as a chapelry within the township of Crompton.<ref name="Shaw GENUKI">{{cite web |url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Shaw/|title=Shaw |publisher=GENUKI|accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> The [[Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica Eleventh Edition|1911 Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica]] describes Shaw as a populous village within the Crompton district.<ref name="1911 Encyclo"/> However due to the urbanisation of the Shaw area, and the establishment of a post office in Shaw itself,<ref name="Oldham Borough Guide">{{cite web |url=http://www.british-publishing.com/Pages/OldhamOG/districts.html |title=Oldham Borough Official Guide; The Borough's Districts |publisher=British-publishing.com |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> the two areas and names merged to form the present day "Shaw and Crompton". The area of Shaw and Crompton is often called Shaw by local communities (and increasingly in maps and literature); this is in contrast to former times when the area was broadly known as Crompton. This contrast can be seen on the markings of prominent historical structures, which only bear the name "Crompton".

Shaw and Crompton contains two separate [[Ward (politics)|political wards]], appropriately named "Shaw" and "Crompton" (to the east and west respectively),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geoplanning.oldham.gov.uk/gis/map.aspx?ACTION=PLANNING |title=Interactive Planning Map |publisher=Oldham.gov.uk |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> and residential suburbs, including [[High Crompton]], [[Rushcroft]], [[Buckstones]], [[Clough, Shaw and Crompton|Clough]], [[Jubilee, Shaw and Crompton|Jubilee]], [[Shaw Side]], [[Wrens Nest]], [[Cowlishaw]], [[Low Crompton]], [[Nook, Shaw and Crompton|Nook]], [[Goats, Shaw and Crompton|Goats]], [[Wood End, Shaw and Crompton|Wood End]] and [[Shore Edge]].

[[Image:PMBShawVista.JPG|center|frame|View of Shaw and Crompton from Dog Hill, Buckstones Road with the areas of Cowlishaw, High Crompton and Ruscroft in the distance and Clough, East Crompton and Buckstones itself in the foreground. The former [[cotton mill]]s belonging to Fulfilment Logistics and [[Littlewoods Shop Direct Group]] respectively, can be seen in the foreground.]]

==Demography==
{{further|[[Demography of Greater Manchester]]}}
