==Economy==
[[Image:LittlewoodsNDC1.jpg|left|thumb|Shaw National Distribution Centre: A major employer of the local and wider communties.]]
Shaw and Crompton has become a base for distribution companies as a result of the town's good transport links, its supply of large, disused mill properties, and its situation between Manchester, Oldham, Rochdale, Lancashire, and West Yorkshire.<ref name="Oldham Borough Guide"/> It is home to the [[Littlewoods Shop Direct Group]]'s [[Shaw National Distribution Centre]], which is a major employer of the local and wider community. The company occupies three former cotton mills and state-of-the-art purpose-built storage and sorting facilities on a {{convert|20|acre|ha|1|sing=on}} complex within the town. In 2007, the site became the retail company's only packing and distribution centre for non-bulk items.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business.guardian.co.uk/story/0,,1771117,00.html|title=Littlewoods sheds 1,200 staff |author=Tran, Mark|publisher=Guardian Unlimited|date=[[2006-05-09]]|accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> It employs nearly 1,000 staff, making it  the Metropolitan Borough of Oldham's largest private employer.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/220/220185_littlewoods_pledges_400_new_jobs_.html |title=Littlewoods pledges 400 new jobs|author=Anon|publisher=''[[Oldham Advertiser]]''|date=[[2006-11-22]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> Children's toy distributors Toy Options and bakers [[Warburtons]] also have distribution centres in the town. 

Warburtons has had one of its 11 major bakeries in Shaw and Crompton since 1965. The "Pennine" bakery produces around 500,000 loaves a week and distributes them to major multiples and independent retailers throughout Greater Manchester, [[Cheshire]], and [[Derbyshire]]. Located on Glebe Street, it employs around 200 staff and produces a wide range of Warburtons bread products.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.warburtons.presscentre.com/Content/Detail.asp?ReleaseID=110254&NewsAreaID=111 |title=Warburtons Bakeries; North West; Pennine |publisher=Warburtons Virtual Press Office |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref>
Until the 1990s, Shaw and Crompton was the home of [[Osram]], the multinational lightbulb manufacturer, which occupied Duke Mill and was a significant employer in the area. Production has since been moved away from the United Kingdom.

Trent Mill Industrial Estate, on the edge of the town near [[Rushcroft]], takes its name from the mill that was once found there. The [[business park]] is home to several small industrial companies. It was partially destroyed by a fire that started in a plastics factory in the early hours of [[April 28]], [[2007]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/6602739.stm|title=Firefighters tackle factory blaze|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=[[2007-04-28]]|accessdate=2007-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham-chronicle.co.uk/NEWSM03.html|title=Inferno wrecks plastics factory|author=Hooton, Richard and Torr, Martyn|publisher=''[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]]''|date=[[2007-04-30]]|accessdate=2007-04-30}}</ref>

On [[August 6]], [[2007]] a {{convert|35000|sqft|sqm|0|sing=on}} [[ASDA]] supermarket opened on the site of the former Dawn Mill.<ref name="ASDA">{{Citation|last =Anon|title=Green store shooting up|newspaper=[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]]|pages=25|year=2007|date=[[2007-04-24]]}}</ref> A derelict row of houses on Eastway was demolished as part of this development. Two houses on Greenfield Lane were also demolished, allowing the existing [[ALDI]] store to expand&mdash;possibly to help it to compete with the new ASDA store. The original planning application was put to a public vote in 2005, and included proposals for 316 parking spaces, improved bus facilities, pedestrian routes linked to Market Street, junction improvements to nearby streets, and the relocation of a local tyre-fitting company.<ref>{{cite press release|title = ASDA Shaw - Your views count | publisher = Dialogue|date=February 2005}}</ref> The supermarket cost [[Pound sterling|GB<U+00A3>]]20million to construct, and is the first ASDA store in the United Kingdom to use [[environmentally friendly]] construction techniques, which [[Wal-Mart]] intends to use as a blueprint for all its new ASDA supermarkets.<ref name="ASDA"/> It incorporates a [[Sustainable forestry|sustainable timber]] frame and an [[Energy conservation|energy-saving]] ventilation system, which together have eradicated the need for 500&nbsp;tonnes of steel and 450&nbsp;tonnes of carbon emissions.<ref name="ASDA"/>

==Landmarks==
Despite its comparatively small size, Shaw and Crompton has several landmarks, including a large war memorial.

===Crompton War Memorials===
====First and Second World Wars====
[[Image:PMBWarMemorial.jpg|right|thumb|Crompton War Memorial.]]
The main Crompton War Memorial, located on the High Street, consists of a [[Granite|Scottish granite]] plinth surmounted by a large bronze statue flanked by two Rolls of Honour containing the 346 names of those from Shaw and Crompton who fought and died in [[World War I]]. Panels listing the Roll of Honour from [[World War II]] were added and unveiled on [[November 12]], [[1950]] by Councillor H. M. Turner.<ref name="Crompton War Memorial">{{cite web |url=http://pmsa.cch.kcl.ac.uk/MR/MR-OLD06.htm |title= Crompton War Memorial |author=[[Public Monuments and Sculpture Association]] |date=[[2003-06-16]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> Commissioned by the Crompton War Memorial Committee, the statue was conceptualised in 1919 by [[Richard Reginald Goulden]], and unveiled on [[April 29]], [[1923]] by [[Ian Standish Monteith Hamilton|General Sir Ian Hamilton]]. The original cost for the memorial alone was GB<U+00A3>4,000, but the total cost, including site and layout, was about GB<U+00A3>6,067.<ref name="Crompton War Memorial"/>

The inscription on the memorial reads:

<center>''IN MEMORY OF THE MEN OF CROMPTON WHO FOUGHT AND GAVE THEIR LIVES TO FREE MANKIND FROM THE OPPRESSION AND BRUTAL TYRANNY OF WAR,. 1914<U+2013>1919.''</center>

The symbolic memorial depicts a group in which the central figure is a man defending the future generations, represented by young children, against foreign aggression, represented by a beast. The memorial is also a time capsule. Inside it is a lead casket containing coins, a copy of the local newspaper, three cops of spun cotton, and a length of cloth manufactured in the local area.<ref name="Changing Face"/>

====Second Boer War====
A second, smaller war memorial is located in Jubilee Gardens. It is dedicated to the soldiers who fought in the [[Second Boer War]]. It consists of a plaque built into a stone wall that is located between two large bushes.

Its inscription reads:
<center>''IN MEMORY OF THE CROMPTON MEN WHO LOST THEIR LIVES IN THE SOUTH AFRICAN WAR 1899<U+2013>1902''</center>

It then lists eight men: four who were "killed in action", two who "died of wounds", and two who "died of disease".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.roll-of-honour.org/Lancashire/ShawBoer.html|title= Crompton South African War Memorial |publisher=Roll-of-Honour.org |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref>

====The Beacon====
[[Image:Shaw & Crompton Beacon.JPG|left|thumb|150px|Shaw and Crompton Beacon]]
In 1995, to mark the 50th anniversary of the ending of the Second World War, a landmark known as The Shaw and Crompton Beacon was erected in Jubilee Gardens. 

The inscription on the plaque below reads:
<center>''THE SHAW AND CROMPTON BEACON<br>ERECTED BY THE PARISH COUNCIL IN 1995 TO<br>COMMEMORATE THE FIFTIETH ANNIVERSARY OF<br>THE ENDING OF WORLD WAR TWO<br><small>THIS PLAQUE WAS PRESENTED BY MEMBERS OF THE BRITISH LEGION</small></center>

===Crompton Moor===
[[Image:Pingot Quarry Waterfall.jpg|right|thumb|Pingot quarry at [[Crompton Moor]] features an un-named [[waterfall]].]]
Spanning approximately {{convert|160|acre|sqkm|1}}, and reaching an elevation of {{convert|1282|ft|m|0}}, [[Crompton Moor]] is one of the largest open spaces run by Oldham Countryside Service.<ref name="Fourmost">{{Citation | last =Steve Duthie|title=Moors to life|newspaper=Fourmost magazine|publisher=HKR magazines|pages=18|year=2007|date=August 2007}}</ref> It is a registered [[Commons|common]] of Greater Manchester,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.defra.gov.uk/wildlife-countryside/issues/common/pdf/greater%20manchester.pdf|title=The Common Lands of Greater Manchester; A Biological Survey|format=pdf|date=|publisher=Rural Surveys Research Unit|accessdate=2007-08-13}}</ref> and, since 2003, a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest|Site of Biological Interest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.try-cycles.co.uk/9.html|title=Northwest Riders (N.W.R.); Revamped outdoor gem relaunched|author=[[Oldham Evening Chronicle]]|publisher=try-cycles.co.uk|date=[[2007]]-[[06-28]]|accessdate=2007-08-13}}</ref>

Brushes Clough and Pingot are former [[coal]] and [[sandstone]] quarries set amongst Crompton Moor.<ref name="Moor1">{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/crompton-moor-walking-trails.pdf|title=Crompton Moor Walking Trails|Publisher=oldham.gov.uk|date=[[2003-06-16]]|accessdate=2007-06-20|format=PDF}}</ref> During the 1970s, quarrying was halted, the land was reclaimed, and thousands of [[pine tree]]s were planted. The area has since been used for recreation, including hiking, orienteering, and mountain biking.<ref name="Moor1"/><ref name="Fourmost"/> Brushes Clough Reservoir was constructed in the 19th century using stone quarried from this site. The area is now managed by [[United Utilities]].<ref name="Moor1"/>

An un-named waterfall (provisionally called Crompton Waterfall) cascades off [[Crompton Moor]] into the now unused Pingot Quarry forming the "Old Brook", a [[tributary]] of the [[River Beal]].<ref name="Fourmost"/><ref name="Moor1"/><ref name="Moor2">{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/crompton-moor-history-trail.pdf |title= Crompton Moor History Trail|format=PDF|Publisher=oldham.gov.uk |date=[[2003-06-16]] |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref>

===Big Lamp===
[[Image:BigLamp.jpg|left|thumb|The Big Lamp as seen in 2006. [[Crompton Moor]] can be seen in the background.]]
The Big Lamp was a six-sided gas-powered public street lamp standing {{convert|20|ft|m|0}} high at the original cross-road junction of Manchester Road, Oldham Road, High Street, and Church Road. It was pulled down on [[June 17]] [[1925]], when electric lighting was introduced.<ref name="Changing Face"/> Its absence was so evident that the adjacent public house, then known as The Kings Arms, was renamed The Big Lamp.<ref name="Shaw pubs">{{cite book|title=A History of Crompton and Shaw Pubs|last=Magee|first=Rob|publisher=Neil Richardson|date=1998|isbn=1-852160-30-6}}</ref>

During the 1990s, the junction was redeveloped to accommodate the new Crompton Way bypass. A large [[roundabout]] was built, and a scaled-down replica of the original Big Lamp was erected in its centre. The new Big Lamp is electrically powered and stands about {{convert|6|ft|m|0}} high. Once the new lamp appeared, the roundabout became known as the Big Lamp Roundabout, and the public house reverted to its original name.<ref name="Shaw pubs"/>

==Transport==
Shaw and Crompton has had a [[railway|rail transport]] line and station since 1863, when it was used mostly for haulage.<ref>{{cite book|first=Jeffrey|last=Wells|title=The Oldham Loop part one: Manchester Victoria to Shaw and Crompton|publisher=Foxline Publishing|date=2002|isbn=978-1-870119-68-9}}</ref> Today [[Shaw and Crompton railway station]] is used by passenger trains running between Rochdale and Manchester on the [[Manchester to Rochdale via Oldham Line|Oldham Loop railway line]]. 

After initially being rejected, plans to turn the line into part of the [[Manchester Metrolink]] were accepted by the government on [[July 6]], [[2006]]. Work is expected to start in 2008.<ref name="Metrolink01">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/manchester/5152948.stm |author=Anon |title=Metrolink extension is announced |publisher=BBC News |date=[[2006-07-06]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> The conversion will be likely to result in the decommissioning of the conventional [[heavy rail]] service on this line, with trams running along most of the existing line, which it is planned to re-route into Oldham town centre.

The bus company [[First Manchester]] provides frequent services to Oldham and Rochdale, with buses running on to the [[Trafford Centre]] and the suburbs of Rushcroft, Wrens Nest, and Buckstones. There is also a 'Shaw Circular' route, bus 403, which is run by Swan's Travel, which serves the smaller roads of Shaw and Crompton.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gmpta.gov.uk/uploads/publications/71/090307.pdf|format=PDF  |title=Oldham local transport public forum |publisher=GMPTE |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> [[Greater Manchester Passenger Transport Executive|GMPTE]] co-ordinates the bus routes in the area. Services which run in the Shaw and Crompton area are:
*58 Rochdale - Shaw - Oldham - Middleton - Trafford Centre (First Manchester)
*59 Rushcroft - Shaw - Oldham - Middleton - Manchester (First Manchester)
*181 Rochdale (First Manchester only) - Shaw - Royton - Chadderton - Manchester (Bluebird/First Manchester)
*182 Rochdale (First Manchester only) - Shaw - Royton - Royal Oldham Hospital - Chadderton - Manchester (Bluebird/First Manchester)
*403 Shaw Circular (Swan's Travel)
*408 Buckstones - Shaw - High Crompton - Royton - Oldham - Abeyhills - Stalybridge (First Manchester)
*435 Buckstones - Shaw - High Crompton - Turf Hill - Rochdale ([[Rossendale Transport]])

Shaw and Crompton is located south of Junction 21 of the [[M62 motorway]], which connects the town with other parts of Greater Manchester, as well as counties of England as far as [[Merseyside]] and [[South Yorkshire]].

==Education==
{{seealso|List of schools in the North West of England}}
Almost every suburb of Shaw and Crompton is served by a school of some kind, including some with religious affiliations. All the schools in the town perform either at or above the national average for test results. [[Crompton House]], a secondary school for 11- to 16-year-olds, also has a [[sixth form college]] of [[further education]] for 16- to 18-year-olds on the same site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crompton-house.oldham.sch.uk/|title=Crompton House School|author=|publisher=crompton-house.oldham.sch.uk|date=|accessdate=2007-07-26}}</ref>

