</div>
Most of the above churches participate in Shaw's annual [[Pentecost|Whit Walks]] event, when congregations, choirs, and brass bands parade through the streets from their respective churches before taking part in one large, communal, inter-church service.

The town centre is also home to a small [[mosque]].

==Community facilities==
[[Image:Cromptonswimmingpool.jpg|thumb|left|Crompton Pool, near the town centre, is a public [[swimming pool]] built in 1899, under the supervision of Crompton Urban District Council.]]
Shaw and Crompton has many communal areas and public facilities, including public parks, sporting establishments, and playing fields. [[Public house]]s in the centre of the town include The Blue Bell, Duke of York, Coach and Horses, and Pineapple.<ref name="Shaw pubs"/> There are many outlying public houses, including The Kings Arms at the Big Lamp, Royal Oak at Cowlishaw, and the Park Inn at Buckstones Road.<ref name="Shaw pubs"/>

Crompton Library is a purpose-built [[library]] housing over 36,000 items including books, CDs, and DVDs that can be borrowed by anyone who lives in the Oldham borough.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/community/libraries/libraries-in-oldham/crompton-library.htm |title=Oldham Libraries; Crompton Library |publisher=oldham.gov.uk |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> It has communal Internet facilities. The library was built in the early 1990s after the original 1907 building, which exists now as [[apartment]]s on Beal Lane, became too small.

There are three main public parks in Shaw and Crompton. Dunwood Park lies alongside the [[Manchester to Rochdale via Oldham Line|Oldham Loop Railway Line]] and has a children's play area, [[bowling green]], and over a mile of wooded pathways along the base of a forested hillside.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dunwoodpark.co.uk/Home.htm|title=Dunwood Park|author=|publisher=dunwoodpark.co.uk|date=|accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref> The land that forms Dunwood Park was presented to Crompton Urban District Council by Captain Abram Crompton J.P. on the [[22 June]], [[1911]], and opened as a park by him on the [[14 September]], [[1912]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.shawcam.co.uk/dunwoodpark.htm|title=Dunwood Park|publisher=shawcam.co.uk|author=|date=|accessdate=2007-07-25}}</ref> High Crompton Park is in [[High Crompton]] and is home to a [[tennis court]], bowling green, children's play area, and gardens. Jubilee Gardens are found in the centre of Shaw and Crompton town centre, behind the Crompton War Memorial. Shaw and Crompton has large areas of land reserved for sporting and communal events; these are located off George Street, Edward Road, and Rushcroft Road respectively.

Shaw Market, located on Westway, is open to market retailers and customers every Thursday, and Saturday morning.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.funforall.co.uk/markets_north_west_england.htm#Manchester|title=Markets North West England; Greater Manchester|publisher=funforall.co.uk|date=2007|accessdate=2007-07-26}}</ref> At other times most of the market area becomes a public car park. The market area has been used occasionally for fun fairs and other events. Shaw and Crompton town has several public sporting establishments. Crompton Pool is a swimming pool built in 1899 on Farrow Street in the town centre,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldham.gov.uk/shaw___royton_area_plan_-_april_04b.pdf |format=PDF|title=Shaw and Royton Area Plan|publisher=Oldham.gov.uk|date =January 2004 |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> and [[Crompton C.C.|Crompton Cricket Club]], is located on Glebe Street in the town.

"Playhouse2" is a 156 seat [[theatre]] in the heart of Shaw and Crompton town centre. It has been the home of the 'Crompton Stage Society' (an amateur theatre company) since 1966. A wide variety of entertainment, professional as well as amateur, is produced each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playhouse2.com/|title=Playhouse2|author=|publisher=playhouse2.com|date=|accessdate=2007-07-27}}</ref>

===Future developments===
Shaw and Crompton town centre is the subject of controversy due to a successful application to convert a local venue into a [[Lap dance|lapdancing]] club, despite its close proximity to a primary school, nursery, and a youth club. Although the proposals caused concern, there were no formal complaints from local residents, the police, or the local council<U+2019>s child protection unit during the application period.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/216/216746_parishioners_join_the_fight_against_lap_dancing_club.html |title=Parishioners Join the Fight Against Lap Dancing Club |author=Appleton, Dave |publisher=''[[Oldham Advertiser]]'' |date=[[2006-10-23]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref> However, what was described as a legally watertight argument from the applicant, as well as assurances about security arrangements, were enough to secure licensing for the venue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oldhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/s/216/216212_lapdancing_a_shaw_thing.html |title=Lapdancing a Shaw Thing |author=Greer, Stuart |publisher=''[[Oldham Advertiser]]'' |date=[[2006-10-09]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref>

Crompton Health Centre is also subject to a development scheme intended to improve [[National Health Service|NHS]] facilities in the town.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oldham.nhs.uk/lift/liftdev/crompton.htm|title=First Schemes to be Developed - Crompton|publisher=[[National Health Service|NHS]]|date=[[2005-11-17]]|accessdate=2007-04-25}}</ref>

==Filmography==
<!-- FAIR USE of FredDibnahStory01.jpg: see image description page at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image:FredDibnahStory01.jpg for rationale --> 
[[Image:FredDibnahStory01.JPG|right|thumb|Title image of ''The Fred Dibnah Story'', showing [[Fred Dibnah|Fred]] himself scaling Briar chimney in front of a backdrop of Shaw and Crompton centre. Circa 1978.]]
Shaw and Crompton has been featured in several British-made television programmes and films:
* The film ''[[The Parole Officer]]'' features a scene in which [[Steve Coogan]] is seen driving a car along Grains Road in Shaw. The scene was filmed near the junction of Grains Road and Buckstones Road at Dog Hill, and the Shaw and Crompton skyline can be clearly seen in the background.
* The first series of the [[BBC]]'s ''[[Common As Muck]]'' featured scenes filmed in the local area. Locations on Market Street, High Street, Rochdale Road, and Westway were used, including the Cricketers [[public house]], Shaw Meat Centre (now Shaw Farm Produce), and Healds (now [[Tesco]]).
* Bolton celebrity steeplejack [[Fred Dibnah]] visited the [[List of Shaw and Crompton Mills|cotton mills of the area]] as part of the BBC documentary ''The Fred Dibnah Story''.<ref>{{cite video
  | people = Dibnah, Fred (Presenter), Haworth, D. (Director)
  | title = The Fred Dibnah Story
  | medium = TV Series
  | publisher =
  | location = Shaw and Crompton
  | date = 1986 }}</ref> The film included Fred's unique approach to the demolition of the [[List of Shaw and Crompton Mills#A-E|Briar and Cape]] chimneys.

==Notable people==
People from Shaw and Crompton are called "Shaytonians" or "Cromptonians".<ref name="Shaw Church"/> The town is the home of Oldham-born actress [[Shobna Gulati]],<ref name="coming">{{cite web |url=http://manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/s/1006/1006070_coming_soon__shaw_tv.html|title=Coming soon - Shaw TV!|publisher=ManchesterEveningNews.co.uk|author=Greer, Stuart|date=[[2007-05-03]] |accessdate=2007-06-20}}</ref> former [[Oldham Athletic A.F.C.|Oldham Athletic]] player and manager [[Andy Ritchie (English footballer)|Andy Ritchie]],<ref name="coming"/> and is the hometown of Kevin O'Toole, a founding member of dance act [[N-Trance]]. [[Tommy Cannon]] and [[Bobby Ball]] also live locally;<ref name="coming"/> Ball owns farm property that overlooks the area. [[Philip Gilbert Hamerton]], an acclaimed etcher, painter, and [[art critic]] was born in the area in 1834.<ref>{{cite book |last=Hamerton |first=P. G. |date=2004 |title=Philip Gilbert Hamerton: an Autobiography, 1834<U+2013>1858 |publisher= Kessinger Publishing}}</ref> 

Although a native of [[Rochdale]], television and movie actress [[Anna Friel]] was a pupil at [[Crompton House|Crompton House Church of England High School]], which lies in the area.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avaxhome.ru/graphics/af_gallery_one.html |title=Anna Friel |publisher=avaxhome.ru |date=[[2006-12-24]] |accessdate=2007-04-03}}</ref>

